publications.name: System Integration and Verification Verdict Automation using Machine Learning
publications.description:
This research paper introduces an innovative approach to tackle the challenge of managing vast log files containing critical information about software application behavior. With log files being essential for understanding an application's functioning, the study focuses on automating the detection of errors within these logs, reducing the burden of manual inspection for developers.

The primary goal is to identify and categorize errors during testing and production phases to ensure proper application behavior. This is achieved by training a machine learning model to distinguish various error types, such as errors, debug messages, info logs, and failures.

To accomplish this, the research utilizes machine learning techniques, including SVM, Multinomial Naive Bayes, and LSTM networks, which excel at capturing the order dependencies present in log data. Specific error types are identified, and verdict generation techniques are applied to provide actionable insights.

The results highlight the effectiveness of this approach, demonstrating that integrating machine learning and classification methods streamlines error detection and resolution, reducing the manual effort required to bring an application into production. This research empowers developers to automate error identification in log files, improving efficiency and ensuring the application stays on course. Overall, it presents a promising solution to the challenges of managing extensive log files in modern software development.
